ing to Fall -- t24 August -- t31 August -- tTerm MRI for Small Preterm Babies: Do Parents Really Want to Know, and Why Has Nobody Asked Them? -- tMeasuring and Communicating Meaningful Outcomes in Neonatology: A Family Perspective -- tPart 5: Coming Home -- tGerm-o-phobia -- tMeanwhile, with My Other Kids … -- tRewriting Your Life -- tA Mother’s Love -- tThe Backpack: The Sequel -- tAfter Violette, Am I a Better Doctor? -- tTattoos, Beer, and Bow Ties: The Limits of Professionalism in Medicine -- t26 September -- tWhat’s Your Dream? -- t22 May 2011 -- tStronger and More Vulnerable: A Balanced View of the Impacts of the NICU Experience on Parents -- tSurvival Guide for Parents -- tPart 6: Neonatology Information for Parents, Families, Clinicians, and All Those Who Care about Babies -- tGetting the Bad Stuff Out -- tSeven Don’ts for Families and Friends Helping Parents -- tThe Best Ways to Help Parents in the NICU -- tEthics and Etiquette in Neonatal Intensive Care -- tNotes -- tGlossary of Common Abbreviations Used in the NICU -- tSelected Bibliography -- tResources and Further Reading0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEvery year in the United States, 12% of all births are preterm births, 5% of all babies need help to breathe at birth, and 3% of neonates are born with at least one severe malformation. Many of these babies are hospitalized in a neonatal intensive care unit. Annie Janvier and her husband, Keith Barrington, are both pediatricians who specialize in the care of these sick babies and are internationally known for their research in this area. In 2005, when their daughter Violette was born extremely prematurely, 4 months before her due date, they faced the situation "from the other side," as parents. Despite knowing the scientific facts, they knew nothing about the experience itself. "Knowing how a respirator works did not help me be the mother of a baby on a respirator," writes Annie. She did not know how to navigate the guilt, the uncertainty, the fears, the predictions of providers, and the responses of friends and family. In a society obsessed with goals, performance, efficiency, and high percentages, she discovered that the daily lack of control that new parents of sick babies face changes their lives. And that, for physician parents, it also changes the way they practice medicine. Most of the articles and books written about premature babies and neonatal intensive care units examine the technological and medical aspects of neonatology. Breathe, Baby, Breathe, however, is written in the voice of a parent-doctor and tells the story of Violette and her parents, alongside the stories of other fragile babies and their families with different journeys and different outcomes. With the story of Violette at the core of the book, the interwoven stories and empirical articles provide essential insights into the medical world of premature birth. This original clever blend of narratives and evidence provides a new, experiential view of the way forward during a parental crisis. The book ends with practical recommendations for clinicians, parents, and families.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aNeonatologistsvBiography. 0aPremature infantsvBiography. 0aPremature infantsxCare. 0aPremature labor. 4aDISCOUNT-C. 7aMEDICAL / Pediatric Emergencies.2bisacsh  abioethics.  aclinical.  acritical.  aend-of-life decisions.  afamily-centered.  aintegrated care.  aintensive.  anarrative ethics.  aneonatal.  aneonatology.  aobstetrics.  apaediatrics.  apalliative.  apediatric.  aperinatology.  aprematurity.1 aAronoff, Phyllis.1 aLantos, John D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeadow, William, econtributor.4ctb4h